Patch Set 3:

> Doesnt't struct mgs_target_info get written to llogs? Is their any
 > limtation if that is the case?

I believe it is sent over the network from a server to the MGS during the connection:

 static const struct req_msg_field *mgs_target_info_only[] = {
        &RMF_PTLRPC_BODY,
        &RMF_MGS_TARGET_INFO
 };
 struct req_format RQF_MGS_TARGET_REG =
        DEFINE_REQ_FMT0("MGS_TARGET_REG", mgs_target_info_only,
                         mgs_target_info_only);

but this is generally fine.  Old clients don't mind getting a larger *request* buffer (they will ignore the part they don't understand).  Getting a larger *reply* buffer than expected is often a problem, because the client doesn't have enough space to RDMA the reply into, but I don't think that is a problem in this case.

So there isn't an unlimited amount of space, but it could grow some KB without problem (I think).  There *is* a check in mgc_set_info_async_server():

        if (KEY_IS(KEY_REGISTER_TARGET)) {
                struct mgs_target_info *mti;

                if (vallen != sizeof(struct mgs_target_info))
                        RETURN(-EINVAL);

It might need to be changed to be something more flexible:

                if (vallen < sizeof(*mti) ||
                    vallen > 2 * sizeof(*mti))
                        RETURN(-EINVAL);

The server should check OBD_CONNECT2_LARGE_NID before sending the large request to avoid triggering the error on connect during upgrade, but this should be very rarely.  You can test cross-version upgrades with:

 Test-Parameters: testgroup=rolling-upgrade-oss
 Test-Parameters: testgroup=rolling-upgrade-mds

Patch Set 28:

(1 comment)

There are a lot of places that do
 if (target_supports_large_nids()) {
      X;
 } else {
      Y;
 }

and I think there is quite a bit of commonality.  e.g "get the nid as a string" or "get the nid as a number".  Maybe a couple of static-inlines could extract the common code.

Generally this looks good.
